            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "@wookayin I found a way. It was actually very simple and I was just being kinda dumb. `bun pm bin -g` gives the path to the globally installed binaries dir. In that directory, there is a symlink to `cli.js` located in the neovim module. It seems that bun creates a symlink in the binaries dir for the path specified in the bin key in the `package.json`.\r\n\r\nI'll turn this into a draft PR and make the changes. The path will end up like this:\r\n\r\n`[bin_path]/neovim-node-host` where `bin_path` is the output of `bun pm bin -g`.\r\n\r\nSounds good?",
            "commit_id": "ebd1e41e7455445fa12c7ab9aa25076ceb0ae04c",
            "created_at": "2024-01-01T21:40:21Z",
            "diff_hunk": "@@ -83,6 +83,17 @@ function! provider#node#Detect() abort\n     let pnpm_opts.job_id = jobstart('pnpm --loglevel silent root -g', pnpm_opts)\n   endif\n \n+  let bun_opts = {}\n+  if executable('bun')\n+    let bun_opts = deepcopy(s:NodeHandler)\n+    let bun_opts.entry_point = '/node_modules/neovim/bin/cli.js'\n+    let bun_config_dir = '/.bun'\n+    let bun_default_path = $HOME . bun_config_dir . '/install' . '/global' . bun_opts.entry_point",
